quotedTweet.rawContent:
J.P. Crawford season adjustments

The entire 2022 Season
.243 AVG / .339 OBP / .336 SLG (103 wRC+)
Opening Day - June 9th, 2023
.235 AVG / .342 OBP / .333 SLG (98 wRC+)

June 10th, 2023 - October 1st, 2023
.285 AVG / .402 OBP / .503 SLG (156 wRC+)

What changed for J.P. Crawford?
36.5 Pull% -> 47.1 Pull% (⬆️ 10.6%)
28.9 Hard% -> 32.5 Hard% (⬆️ 3.6%)

J.P. Crawford finished in the 16th and 21st percentiles in Barrel% and Hard-Hit% during the 2023 season, respectively. Yet, it worked.

From OD-6/9, J.P. hit .280 at home.
From 6/10-EOS, J.P. hit .281 at home.
From OD-6/9, J.P. slugged .380 at home.
From 6/10-EOS, J.P. slugged .491 at home.

He found a way to slug at T-Mobile Park.
He was even better away from T-Mobile Park.

He’ll still go the other way on pitches, but when he’s looking to do serious damage, he pulls the ball as hard as he can. It works.

His overall season numbers vs 2022:
46.5 GB% -> 39.6 GB% (⬇️ 6.9%)
18.2 FB% -> 23.7 FB% (⬆️ 5.5%)
27.2 LD% -> 28.0 LD% (⬆️ 0.8%)
33.7 Pull% -> 43.2 Pull% (⬆️ 9.5%)
29.7 HardHit% -> 36.2 HardHit% (⬆️ 6.5%)
2.0 Barrel% -> 4.8 Barrel% (⬆️ 2.8%)
32.4 SS% -> 35.3 SS% (⬆️ 2.9%)
85.1 Avg EV -> 88.3 Avg EV (⬆️ 3.2 MPH)
8.9 Avg LA -> 15.1 Avg LA (⬆️ 6.2 Degrees)

As long as his adjustments carry over to 2024, there’s no reason to believe J.P. won’t replicate his 2023 success, or even top it.

rawContent:
Etienne Leopold Trouvelot's story serves as an early lesson in the unintended consequences of importing non-native species for economic or scientific purposes. His initial aim to explore the potential of gypsy moths for silk production led to an ecological nightmare that we're still grappling with today. This example highlights the importance of thoroughly understanding an ecosystem before introducing new elements into it, as the ripple effects can be devastating and long-lasting.

Interestingly, Trouvelot's career pivot from entomology to astronomy after the gypsy moth debacle is a testament to the multifaceted nature of scientific curiosity. While his work in entomology had catastrophic consequences, his contributions to astronomy were notable and earned him fellowship in the American Academy of Arts and Sciences. This duality serves as a reminder that the impacts of scientific exploration can be both beneficial and detrimental, often depending on factors beyond the control or foresight of the individuals involved.

user.rawDescription: Daily history lessons. Education through memes!

rawContent:
This is a photo of a group of workers attempting to control the gypsy moth population by throwing an egg-scraping party to remove egg masses before they hatch on a Dexter elm tree in Malden, MA in 1894 or 1895.

The Civil War (1861-1865) disrupted many of the supply chains for cotton, leaving northern textile mills looking for a new source of raw fiber. Many owners turned to silk, including a Frenchman named Etienne Leopold Trouvelot, who had settled outside of Boston. In 1869, Trouvelot imported gypsy moths and kept them in the woods near his house. 

Unfortunately, they proved to not be a reliable source for silk. A few inadvertently escaped and spread to surrounding areas. Over the next few decades, the gypsy moth became one of the most destructive pests of hardwood trees in North America. It is currently classified as one of the 100 most destructive invasive species in the world.

After the whole unleashing of an invasive species, Trouvelot lost interest in entomology (the study of insects) and got into astronomy. He was supposedly inspired after witnessing several auroras in 1870. At the time of his death, he had created 7,000 quality astronomical illustrations, some of which were published. In 1877, he was elected as a fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
